.TH "DRUNK" 7 "February 2026" "atomdns handlers" "atomdns authors"

.SH "NAME"
.PP
\fIdrunk\fP \- test client behavior

.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.PP
\fIdrunk\fP sits in between a handler that answers a query and the client, any response can be delayed, dropped or truncated.

.SH "SYNTAX"
.PP
.RS

.nf
drunk {
    drop [/N]
    truncate [/M]
    delay [/L [DURATION]]
}

.fi
.RE

.IP \(bu 4
\fB\fCdrop\fR: drop every /\fBN\fP query, the default is one in four (/4).
.IP \(bu 4
\fB\fCtruncate\fR: truncate every /\fBM\fP query, the default is /4.
.IP \(bu 4
\fB\fCdelay\fR: delay every /\fBL\fP query for \fBDURATION\fP, the default for is /2 and the default for \fBDURATION\fP is 100ms.


.SH "EXAMPLES"
.PP
Drop every 1 in 3 queries to \fB\fCexample.org\fR:

.PP
.RS

.nf
example.org {
    drunk {
        drop /3
    }
    whoami
}

.fi
.RE

.PP
Or even shorter if the defaults suit you. Note this only drops queries, it does not delay them.

.PP
.RS

.nf
example.org {
    drunk
    whoami
}

.fi
.RE

.PP
Delay 1 in 3 queries for 50ms

.PP
.RS

.nf
example.org {
    drunk {
        delay /3 50ms
    }
    whoami
}

.fi
.RE

.PP
Delay 1 in 3 and truncate 1 in 5.

.PP
.RS

.nf
example.org {
    drunk {
        delay /3 5ms
        truncate /5
    }
    whoami
}

.fi
.RE
